						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Selected-publications/In-what-ways-will-civil-society-participation-contribute-to-influencing-outcomes-under-the-African-Peer-Review-Mechanism" title="In what ways will civil society participation contribute to influencing outcomes under the African Peer Review Mechanism?" alt="link">In what ways will civil society participation contribute to influencing outcomes under the African Peer Review Mechanism?</a></h2>

	
					<p> Mon, 23 May 2005 | This paper provides general information on the New Partnership for Africas Development (Nepad) and the African Peer Review Mechanism (APRM) in order to facilitate active participation in its processes. It draws on the Nepad policy documents, a range of commentaries and relevant survey data, and summarises key aspects of the Nepad vision and the APRM on the basis that they appear to be insufficiently clear to many individuals, organisations and legislatures potentially affected by them or interested in engaging.</p>
							<p><span class="date">7/06/2005</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Selected-publications/In-what-ways-will-civil-society-participation-contribute-to-influencing-outcomes-under-the-African-Peer-Review-Mechanism">Read more...</a>
